40|$|International audienceWe {{report a}} novel fat face <b>illusion</b> <b>that</b> when two {{identical}} {{images of the}} same face are aligned vertically, the face at the bottom appears 'fatter'. This <b>illusion</b> emerged when <b>the</b> faces were shown upright, but not inverted, {{with the size of}} <b>the</b> <b>illusion</b> being 4 %. When the faces were presented upside down, <b>the</b> <b>illusion</b> did not emerge. Also, when upright clocks were shown in the same vertically aligned fashion, we did not observe <b>the</b> <b>illusion,</b> indicating <b>that</b> <b>the</b> fat <b>illusion</b> does not generalize to every category of canonically upright objects with similar geometric shape as a face...|$|R
